data.content:
`IFormFile` buffers into memory. For large uploads, bypass it entirely and stream the multipart body to disk using `MultipartReader`.

**1. Configure Kestrel limits** (`Program.cs`):

```csharp
builder.WebHost.ConfigureKestrel(o =>
{
    o.Limits.MaxRequestBodySize = 2L * 1024 * 1024 * 1024; // 2 GB
});
```

**2. Stream-to-disk endpoint**:

```csharp
app.MapPost("/upload", async (HttpRequest request) =>
{
    // Validate content type
    if (!request.HasFormContentType ||
        !MediaTypeHeaderValue.TryParse(request.ContentType, out var mt) ||
        string.IsNullOrEmpty(mt.Boundary.Value))
    {
        return Results.BadRequest("Expected a multipart/form-data request.");
    }

    var boundary = HeaderUtilities.RemoveQuotes(mt.Boundary.Value).ToString();
    var reader = new MultipartReader(boundary, request.Body);

    MultipartSection? section;
    while ((section = await reader.ReadNextSectionAsync()) != null)
    {
        if (!ContentDispositionHeaderValue.TryParse(section.ContentDisposition, out var cd)
            || !cd.IsFileDisposition())
            continue;

        // Sanitize the filename
        var fileName = Path.GetFileName(cd.FileName.Value);
        var savePath = Path.Combine("/tmp/uploads", fileName!);

        await using var fs = new FileStream(savePath, FileMode.Create);
        await section.Body.CopyToAsync(fs);          // streams in chunks — no full buffering
    }

    return Results.Ok("Upload complete.");
})
.DisableAntiforgery();                                // required for minimal API file uploads
```

**3. Key NuGet / using directives**:

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.WebUtilities;              // MultipartReader
using Microsoft.Net.Http.Headers;                     // MediaTypeHeaderValue, etc.
```

**Why this works:** `MultipartReader` reads the raw body stream section-by-section, and `CopyToAsync` pipes each section to disk in 80 KB chunks (default). Memory usage stays flat regardless of file size.

**Other things to watch:**

| Concern | Fix |
|---|---|
| Reverse proxy (nginx/IIS) body limits | Set `client_max_body_size 2g;` or `maxAllowedContentLength` |
| Request timeout on slow connections | Increase `RequestHeadersTimeout` / `KeepAliveTimeout` |
| Malicious filenames | Always `Path.GetFileName()` — never trust `cd.FileName` directly |
| Progress tracking | Wrap the stream with a counting decorator and report via SSE or polling |
